Descriptor: Thousands of people take to the streets of downtown Oakland to protest of President Trump's inaguration on Jan. 20. By evening, a smaller group clashes with police, but only one arrest is reported.
In San Francisco, thousands gather at several events to protest President Trump's inaguration. A a long chain of people try to link hands across the Golden Gate Bridge in a peaceful protest.
About a dozen people handcuff themselves to Caltrain tracks in San Francisco — they have to be cut free — to protest President Trump's Jan. 20 inaguration. Eleven are arrested.
Thousands of students, faculty and members of the UC Berkeley community meet on campus for a peaceful rally against President Trump's inaguration.

Tens of thousands of people take to the streets of San Francisco on Jan. 21, the day after President Trump took office, in one of a series of Women's Marches held around the world to support for women's rights.
In one of the largest Oakland protests in recent memory, tens of thousands of particpants gather for the city's Women's March, with many denouncing President Trump's inaguration.

Even in Bay Area suburbs, crowds join the Women's March protests on Jan. 21. Several hundred people, joined by several state senators, attend a rally in Walnut Creek, where protests don't typically happen.
Hundreds of people descend on San Francisco International Airport on Jan. 28 to protest President Trump's ban on travel from seven predominantly Muslim countries.
Hundreds show up outside an Islamic center in Alameda to protest President Trump's travel ban.
On Jan. 30, hundreds of Google employees at the tech giant's Mountain View headquarters protest President Trump's executive order restricting immigration from seven predominantly Muslim countries.

Damages: $100,000 on Berkeley's campus, thousands more in Berkeley proper.
Descriptor: Hundreds of protestors gather at UC Berkeley to protest a planned speech by the far-right provocateur (then with Breibart News) Milo Yiannopoulos. Masked anarchists tear down fences and smash windows at the student center, forcing the event to be canceled.

On March 4, dozens of supporters of President Trump gather at Berkeley's Civic Center Park but are greatly outnumberd by counter-demonstrators. Fights break out, bricks are thrown and there are arrests for assault with a deadly weapon.
Several thousand people gathered March 4 at San Jose's City Hall for a lunctime rally to kick off International Women's Day.
On International Women's Day, a couple hundred protestors gather at UC Berkeley's Sproul Plaza to rally for abortion rights and other issues.
On March 8, International Women's Day — or "A Day Without a Woman," as protestors called it — hundreds of women go on strike to protest sexism and gender inequalities in San Francisco.
On International Women's Day, hundreds of women March 8, joined by male supporters, marched through the streets of Oakland to rail against sexism and demand gender equity, among other causes.

In the second pro-President Trump rally in Berkeley in as many months, right-wingers, liberals and antifa -- anti-fascists --clash at Civc Center Park before violence spills to the streets of Berkeley. Twenty people are arrested, including two on outstanding warrants from a violent March 4 protest.
